<div>
    <h2>What is it</h2>
    <p>
        Open source tool that backs up MySQL RDS instances in form of S3
        objects, which allows to replicate RDS across regions or AWS
        accounts. Driven by
        <a href="http://aws.amazon.com/swf">AWS Simple Workflow</a>
        , it does so by
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>Take a snapshot of RDS instance to backup</li>
            <li>Launch a new RDS instance with snapshot</li>
            <li>
                Launch an EC2 instance that can reach new RDS instance
            </li>
            <li>
                If RDS instance is big enough, launch an HDFS cluster
            </li>
            <li>
                Execute mysqldump command on EC2 instance against new
                RDS instance and save result to disk or HDFS cluster
            </li>
            <li>Upload mysqldump result to specified S3</li>
            <li>
                If the 2 steps above fails, repeat them above until
                successful or retry limit is breached
            </li>
            <li>
                Terminate new RDS instance, EC2 instance and optional
                HDFS cluster
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
        To restore RDS instance from S3 object, similar but reversed
        steps are followed.
    </p>
    <p>
        This website is a quick demo of DataMung. Here you may try
        backing up a MySQL RDS instance under your AWS account.
    </p>
    <p>
    &nbsp;
    </p>
    <h2>Get started</h2>
    <h3>Choose what to do</h3>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <ol>
                <input type="radio" name="actonType" value="BACKUP_INSTANCE"
                    id="actionRadioBackupInstance" />
                <label for="actionRadioBackupInstance">
                    Backup an RDS MySQL instance to S3
                    object
                </label>
            </ol>
            <ol>
                <input type="radio" name="actonType" value="BACKUP_SNAPSHOT"
                    id="actionRadioBackupSnapshot" />
                <label for="actionRadioBackupSnapshot">
                    Convert an RDS MySQL snapshot to S3
                    object
                </label>
            </ol>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <h3>Input an AWS credential:</h3>
    <table border="0" cellpadding="2" cellspading="4">
        <tr>
            Input an AWS credential:
            AWS access key id
            AWS secret key

            The
            credential must have permissions to:

            List, launch and
            terminate RDS instances
            List, create and delete RDS snapshot
            <td>AWS access key id: </td>
            <td>
                <input type="text" name="awsAccessKeyId" size="20" />
            </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>AWS secret key: </td>
            <td>
                <input type="text" name="awsAccessKeyId" size="50" />
            </td>
        </tr>
    </table>
    <p>
        The credential must have permissions to:
        <ol>
            <li>List, launch and terminate RDS instances</li>
            <li>List, create and delete RDS snapshot</li>
            <li>Launch EC2 instance</li>
            <li>List S3 buckets</li>
            <li>Upload, download and delete S3 object</li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
        This demo website does not store any information
        permanently. The
        IAM and all other information about RDS,
        EC2 and S3 will be
        temporarily
        stored in memory and thrown
        away
        after process
        finishes.
    </p>
    <p>
        <button type="submit">Continue...</button>
    </p>
</div>